@page
@model PrivacyModel
@{
    ViewData["Title"] = "Evolution of Cloud Computing";
}
<style>
    body {
        font-family: 'Segoe UI', Tahoma, Geneva, Verdana, sans-serif;
        line-height: 1.6;
        color: #333;
        background-color: #f9f9f9;
    }

    .intro {
        background-color: #e8f5e9;
        border-left: 5px solid #43a047;
        padding: 20px;
        margin-bottom: 30px;
        border-radius: 8px;
        box-shadow: 0 4px 6px rgba(0,0,0,0.1);
    }

    .timeline {
        display: flex;
        flex-direction: column;
    }

    .era {
        flex-basis: calc(100% - 20px);
        background-color: #ffffff;
        border-radius: 8px;
        padding: 20px;
        margin-bottom: 25px;
        box-shadow: 0 4px 10px rgba(0,0,0,0.08);
        border-left: 5px solid #1e88e5;
        transition: transform 0.3s ease;
    }

        .era:hover {
            transform: translateY(-5px);
        }

    h2 {
        color: #2e7d32;
        font-size: 2.2em;
        margin-bottom: 15px;
    }

    .era h3 {
        color: #1565c0;
        font-size: 1.5em;
        margin-bottom: 10px;
    }

    p {
        margin-bottom: 10px;
        font-size: 1.05em;
    }
</style>
<div class="container">
    <div class="intro">
        <h2>Evolution of Cloud Computing</h2>
        <p>Cloud computing has undergone significant evolution since its inception. This timeline highlights key developments and shifts in cloud technology and adoption.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="timeline">
        <div class="era">
            <h3>1960s-1970s: Mainframe Computing</h3>
            <p>The concept of shared computing resources emerged with mainframes, allowing multiple users to access centralized computing power.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="era">
            <h3>1990s: Grid Computing</h3>
            <p>Grid computing introduced the idea of leveraging multiple computers to solve complex problems, laying groundwork for distributed computing.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="era">
            <h3>Early 2000s: Utility Computing</h3>
            <p>The concept of offering computing resources as a metered service, similar to traditional utilities like electricity or water, gained traction.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="era">
            <h3>Mid-2000s: Cloud Computing Emerges</h3>
            <p>Amazon Web Services (AWS) launched in 2006, marking the beginning of modern cloud computing. Google and Microsoft soon followed with their own cloud platforms.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="era">
            <h3>2010s: Cloud Adoption and Diversification</h3>
            <p>Cloud services expanded rapidly, with the emergence of public, private, and hybrid cloud models. SaaS, PaaS, and IaaS became established service models.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="era">
            <h3>Late 2010s-Present: Serverless and Edge Computing</h3>
            <p>Serverless computing and edge computing emerge as new paradigms, pushing cloud capabilities closer to end-users and enabling more efficient resource utilization.</p>
        </div>
    </div>
</div>